You wake up before you remember why. A sharp sound cuts through the room. Knocking. Again. Harder. The door is kicked open. Cold white light spills across the floor like a surgical incision. “You are under arrest, Ari Kessler. You are suspected of unauthorized inference and storage of biological signals, resulting in severe violations of personal autonomy and privacy.” For a moment, your mind refuses to accept the words. You designed systems to translate thoughts into worlds, not into prisons. [[Give yourself a punch.]] [[Run.]]You clench your fist and punch yourself in the cheek. Pain blooms, sharp and undeniable. This is not a dream. A middle-aged police officer steps into the room. He glances at a translucent screen. “Ari Kessler. Thirty-seven. Principal developer of the Generative Interactive System at HoloForge.” He looks up. “The mind behind HoloForge’s creative engine. Correct?” [[Why am I arrested?]]“You have no right to know,” the officer says. [[Detaining me will not solve this.]]The officer studies your face. “Most people say that.” [[Detaining me will not solve this.]]The officer says, “Then here’s the deal.” A small implant glints in his hand. “We install a tracker. You stay in Saarbrücken. Seventy-two hours. Find the real source, or the charges stand.” Your freedom shrinks to a countdown. [[It's unfair.]] [[Deal.]]The officer shrugs. “Fairness comes after containment.” You realize this isn’t justice. It’s risk management. [[Deal.]]You nod. Fear settles in, not panic, but pressure. You consider who might help you trace the leak. One name comes to mind, Dr. Elara Novik. Her research could help. [[Message Dr. Elara Novik.]] [[Message no one.]]You send an encrypted message. “Dr. Novik, it’s Ari. I used to work at your lab. I was hoping we could talk in person about something. It’s urgent.” [[Go home]]You close the interface. No messages sent. No witnesses. No help. You could have contacted someone, but you will not drag anyone else into this. He notices your reaction. “Am I talking too much, sir?” [[No, thank you.]]You finish the last sip and rise from the stool. You step out, keeping your thoughts to yourself. [[Next day.]]A response appears. It contains a short encrypted payload. It feels familiar. You recognize the signature. And… you actually have CS degree, but work in policy?" She laughs softly. "Yes. Math helps me understand the system, regulations help me protect people. The city blurs past as a neon haze, indifferent to your flight. You change locations constantly, staying off the grid. [[End: Break down]]Weeks pass. Users report subtle, intrusive behaviors. Ephemeral states continue to leak. Internal teams scramble, but the platform’s flaws remain. There is no permanent fix. HoloForge falters. PR statements fail. Board meetings dissolve into blame. Eventually, the platform is shut down. The system you designed, once promising, is offline and the problems were never truly solved.
